Step 1: Identify the quick assets from the balance sheet. Quick assets typically include Cash on Hand, Bank Deposits, Interest Receivable, and Accounts Receivable (excluding Inventory).

Step 2: From the table at the end of the reporting period, the values are:
• Cash on Hand: 2,602,624.45  
• Bank Deposits: 4,283,110.81  
• Interest Receivable: 15,023.59  
• Accounts Receivable: 2,117,339.65  

Step 3: Sum the quick assets:  
2,602,624.45 + 4,283,110.81 = 6,885,735.26  
6,885,735.26 + 15,023.59 = 6,900,758.85  
6,900,758.85 + 2,117,339.65 = 9,018,098.50  

Step 4: Identify the total current liabilities from the table:  
• Total Current Liabilities: 378,850.51

Step 5: Calculate the Quick Ratio:  
Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Current Liabilities  
= 9,018,098.50 / 378,850.51  
≈ 23.79

Thus, the quick ratio as of the end of the reporting period is approximately 23.79.
